author: Al Jazeera English
description:
South Korea marks one year since former President Yoon Suk Yeol’s brief martial law decree, which lasted less than seven hours but triggered impeachment and a snap election.
President Lee Jae Myung says the country has recovered through a “Revolution of Light”.
Opponents of martial law held candlelight vigils calling for unresolved issues to be addressed.
Analysts say political divisions persist, with one side demanding an “end to insurrection” and the other calling for “Yoon Again”.
Yoon’s supporters continue rallies blaming repeated impeachments for the crisis.
Yoon and former officials remain on trial over their alleged roles in attempting to impose martial law.
His former party has issued an apology, with some members cutting ties with him.

Al Jazeera’s Jack Barton reports from Seoul.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Leaders of the six-nation Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) met in Manama, Bahrain, for their annual summit.
Security and economic cooperation were top priorities.
This was the first full gathering since Israel’s airstrike on Hamas leaders in Qatar in September.
The GCC emphasised collective security, stating any threat to one member is a threat to all.
Support for international efforts to end the Gaza war and provide aid to Palestinians was reaffirmed.
Economic diversification and progress towards a Gulf Common Market and Customs Union were also discussed.
Experts note that regional rivalries and tensions with Iran continue to challenge the GCC’s goals.

Al Jazeera’s Charles Stratford reports.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
India, home to the world’s second-largest workforce, is implementing its biggest labour changes in decades.
The government has compressed dozens of laws into four simplified codes.
It says the overhaul will attract investment. 
This will be vital after U.S. President Donald Trump imposed 50 percent tariffs on Indian goods.
The reforms include minimum wages, equal pay and expanded social security. 
But unions say the codes will only strengthen employers' control and accuse the government of 'deceptive fraud'.
So, will the changes increase India’s global competitiveness by streamlining rules?
Or could they create new risks for workers and productivity?

Presenter: Adrian Finighan

Guests:
Harshil Sharma -- Labour economist who specialises in reforms and welfare

Surbhi Kesar -- Senior Lecturer in Economics at SOAS University of London

Sudip Dutta -- National Secretary of the Centre of Indian Trade Unions

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Israel says the Rafah crossing with Egypt will reopen soon, but only for Palestinians leaving Gaza.
It has not said when people will be allowed to return, despite the ceasefire deal requiring two-way access.
Egypt denies coordinating with Israel on reopening the crossing.
The move heightens fears among Palestinians in Gaza of permanent displacement amid ongoing Israeli attacks.
Many Palestinians worry they must choose between unbearable living conditions and leaving with no guarantee of return.
Thousands who previously fled Gaza remain stranded outside, unable to go back.
Analysts say Israel is selectively implementing the ceasefire terms, prioritising its own conditions over Palestinian and regional concerns.

Al Jazeera’s Hani Mahmoud reports from Gaza City while Nour Odeh reports from Amman.
Hussein Haridy is a Former Assistant to Egypt's Foreign Ministry.
He says Egypt is willing to cooperate with a European AND Palestinian taskforce to operate the Rafah crossing. 

Subscribe to o
title: Israel says Rafah crossing to open for Palestinian exits as Egypt denies any coordination

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
US President Donald Trump and Secretary of Defence Pete Hegseth have doubled down on US military strikes on alleged Venezuelan drug-smuggling vessels. Hegseth defended a reported second strike on a boat in September, blaming the 'fog of war' for not knowing there were survivors in the water when it was ordered. The US has been targeting vessels in the Caribbean it says are trafficking drugs. More than 80 people have been killed in the attacks since September. Venezuela's government denies any links to drug trafficking. Speaking at a cabinet meeting at the White House, US President Donald Trump didn't rule out future attacks on Venezuela. 

Al Jazeera’s Alan Fisher reports from the White House.
